You are debugging a production issue where a high-throughput microservice is experiencing silent data loss and unexpected `null` returns under high memory pressure. A developer implemented a custom cache to avoid heavy locking, wrapping a standard map with `WeakReference` values to allow the JVM to reclaim cached objects when heap memory runs low:

java
public class CustomConcurrentCache<K, V> {
    private final Map<K, WeakReference<V>> map = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public void put(K key, V value) {
        map.put(key, new WeakReference<>(value));
    }

    public V get(K key) {
        WeakReference<V> ref = map.get(key);
        return ref != null ? ref.get() : null;
    }
}


During a load test, many active keys suddenly start returning `null` even though the keys themselves are still in active use by the system.

You are debugging a production issue where database state updates are silently skipped. A developer implemented a custom tracked collection `TransactionalList<T>` inside a Spring Boot application to monitor list mutations and flush them asynchronously to the database within a separate transaction using Spring's proxy annotations:

java
@Service
public class OrderService {
    @Transactional
    public void processOrder(Order order) {
        TransactionalList<Item> items = new TransactionalList<>(order.getItems());
        items.add(new Item("Gift Pack"));
        persistChangesAsync(items);
    }

    @Async
    @Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
    public void persistChangesAsync(TransactionalList<Item> items) {
        // Code to persist tracking records to DB
    }
}


During load testing, you notice that `persistChangesAsync` runs on the caller's main thread instead of a separate thread, and the new transaction is never opened, causing the database updates to roll back if the parent transaction fails.
